[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Sicilian Defense, Old Sicilian Variation"]
[Black "Old Sicilian Variation (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. c3
{ Preparing d4. } 3... d6 4. Be2 { Not a bad move at all. } 4... Nf6
{ Attacking  e4  . } 5. d4
{ The best move, leaving  e4  unprotected on purpose. } 5... Nxe4
{ This blunder will cost Black a piece soon! } 6. d5
{ Attacking the Knight while opening the 4th rank. } 6... Ne5
{ Saving the Knight, but opening the  a4  -  e8  diagonal.   6...Nxf2  fails to  7.Kxf2  @@StartBracket@@+4.5@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Nxe5
{ Trading Knights first. The best move according to the engine, and the move with the higest winrate. }
7... dxe5 8. Qa4+
{ Check, forking King and Knight! The Queen makes use of the opened rank and diagonal! }
8... Bd7 9. Qxe4
{ White won a piece for a pawn @@StartBracket@@+5.5@@EndBracket@@. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Sicilian Defense, Old Sicilian Variation"]
[Black "Old Sicilian Variation (2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. c3
{ Preparing d4. } 3... d6 4. d4 { Challenging Black's center. } 4... cxd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns. } 5. cxd4 g6
{ With the idea to fianchetto the Bishop next move. } 6. Bc4
{ Keeping an eye on  f7  , a rather dubious move. } 6... Bg7 7. O-O Bg4
{ Attacking the Knight on  f3  while pinning it to the Queen. A poor move. } 8.
Bxf7+ { A temporary Bishop sacrifice! Luring the King to  f7  . } 8... Kxf7 9.
Ng5+
{ Checking the King while creating a discovered attack on the Bishop on  g4  . }
9... Ke8 10. Qxg4
{ Black's King will probably be stuck in the middle for the rest of the game @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Sicilian Defense, Old Sicilian Variation"]
[Black "Old Sicilian Variation (3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. c3
{ Preparing d4. } 3... d6 4. d4 { Challenging Black's center. } 4... cxd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns. } 5. cxd4 Bg4
{ Attacking the Knight on  f3  , pinning it to the Queen. This is a poor move. }
6. d5
{ Attacking the Knight in order to open up the  a4  -  e8  diagonal for the light-squared Bishop on  f1  . }
6... Ne5
{ Increasing the pressure on  f3  . This natural looking move has been played a lot. But it is in fact a game-ending blunder! }
7. Nxe5
{ Capturing the Knight and threatening to capture the Bishop on  g4  , while offering a Queen sacrifice! }
7... Bxd1
{ 7...Qa5+  should be answered with  8.Bd2!!  Bxd1  9.Bxa5  , e.g. followed by  9...dxe5?  10.Bb5  Double Bishops Mate! }
8. Bb5+ Qd7 { A forced move. } 9. Bxd7+ Kd8 10. Nxf7+
{ Forking King and Rook. } 10... Kxd7 11. Kxd1
{ The Rook on  h8  can be captured later. White is totally winning @@StartBracket@@+9.0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Sicilian Defense, Old Sicilian Variation"]
[Black "Old Sicilian Variation (4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. c3
{ Preparing d4. } 3... e6 4. d4 { Challenging Black's center. } 4... cxd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns. } 5. cxd4 a6
{ This move is too passive. It prevents Bb5, but that's not even a good move! It allows White to gain space in the center with tempo.   A move like  5...g6  is equally bad for the same reasons @@StartBracket@@+3.5@@EndBracket@@. }
6. d5 { Attacking the Knight. } 6... exd5 { Trading a pair of pawns. } 7. exd5
{ Attacking the Knight once again. } 7... Qa5+
{ A popular zwischenzug. But this only makes things worse for Black... } 8. Nc3
{ Blocking the check, renewing the threat to capture the Knight on  c6  next move. Material is equal, but Stockfish 13 likes White a lot and even suggests to sacrifice the Knight on  c6  as Black @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Sicilian Defense, Old Sicilian Variation"]
[Black "Old Sicilian Variation (5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. c3
{ Preparing d4. } 3... e6 4. d4 { Challenging Black's center. } 4... cxd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns. } 5. cxd4 Nf6
{ Developing a piece while attacking White's pawn on  e4  . } 6. Nc3
{ Defending the pawn on  e4  . } 6... Bb4
{ Attacking the defender of  e4  while pinning it to the King. } 7. Bd3
{ Defending  e4  with the Bishop instead. } 7... O-O
{ By far the most played move. But this is actually a blunder! } 8. e5
{ Attacking the Knight on  f6  while opening the diagonal for the Bishop on  d3  . Less than 10% of players found this move! }
8... Nd5 { The most logical reply, increasing the pressure on  c3  . } 9. Bxh7+
{ A piece sacrifice! By playing  e5  earlier, White in fact removed one of the defenders of  h7  , namely the Knight. }
9... Kxh7
{ 9...Kh8  10.Ng5  Nxc3  11.bxc3  Bxc3+  12.Kf1  is the alternative.  12...Bxa1  would be a game-ending blunder, in view of  13.Qh5  , followed by checkmate in a few moves. }
10. Ng5+ Kg8 11. Qh5 { Threatening checkmate on  h7  . } 11... Re8
{ Creating an escape square for the King. But this move loses to a mate-in-5!   11...Qxg5  would be very interesting. After  12.Bxg5  Nxc3  13.bxc3  Bxc3+  , Black might have a chance to survive the attack. Feel free to use an engine to get a better understanding of this complicated position @@StartBracket@@+4.5@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Qxf7+ Kh8 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Qh7+ Kf8 15. Qh8+ Ke7 16. Qxg7# *

