[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Sicilian Defense, Old Sicilian Variation"]
[Black "Old Sicilian Variation, Nyezhmetdinov-Rossolimo Attack (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. Bb5
{ Nyezhmetdinov-Rossolimo Attack } 3... d6
{ Self-pinning the Knight on  c6  . This position can also occur via the Sicilian Defense, Moscow Variation:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.Bb5  Nc6  . }
4. O-O { A good move and the move with the highest winrate for White. } 4... g6
{ Not the most accurate move... } 5. d4 { Challenging the center. } 5... cxd4
{ Trading pawns. } 6. Qxd4
{ It is important to capture with the Queen, in order to keep the attack going with an attack on the Rook on  h8  ! The Knight on  c6  can't capture the Queen since it is pinned to the King. }
6... Nf6 { Making it impossible for the Queen to capture the Rook on  a8  . }
7. e5 { Attacking the Knight with the e-pawn. } 7... dxe5
{ Capturing White's center pawn. } 8. Bxc6+
{ Trading Bishops.   8.Qxd8+  will end in the same position. } 8... bxc6 9.
Qxd8+ { And exchanging Queens. } 9... Kxd8 10. Nxe5
{ The point of the whole sequence of moves: Black lost his castling rights and can't defend both the pawn on  c6  and the pawn on  f7  . White will be up a pawn @@StartBracket@@+1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
