[White "2. Sicilian Defense, Old Sicilian Variation"]
[Black "Old Sicilian Variation, Nyezhmetdinov-Rossolimo Attack, Fianchetto Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. Bb5
{ Nyezhmetdinov-Rossolimo Attack } 3... g6 { Fianchetto Variation } 4. O-O Bg7
5. c3 { Preparing d4. } 5... e6
{ Not the most accurate move. Black's light-squared Bishop will have a hard time to get out. }
6. d4 { Creating a strong center. } 6... cxd4 { Trading a pair of pawns. } 7.
cxd4 Nge7 { Hoping to castle next move. } 8. d5
{ Increasing the pressure, attacking the Knight on  c6  with a pawn. } 8...
exd5
{ Trading pawns is a blunder. This opens up the e-file while Black's King still hasn't castled yet!   8...Ne5  would have been a better move for Black. The game could have continued with  9.dxe6  fxe6  10.Nxe5  Bxe5  @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
9. exd5
{ Opening up the e-file while attacking the Knight on  c6  once again. } 9...
Ne5 { 9...O-O  is the best move for Black, that's how bad his position is! }
10. d6
{ Attacking yet another piece with the d-pawn, while blocking the diagonal for the light-squared Bishop on  c8  . }
10... N7c6 11. Bxc6 { By far the best move to keep the attack going. } 11...
bxc6 { 11...Nxc6  12.Re1+  Kf8  @@StartBracket@@+6.5@@EndBracket@@. } 12. Nxe5
{ Trading the second pair of Knights. } 12... Bxe5 13. Re1
{ Attacking the Bishop while pinning it to the King. Black will soon lose the Bishop @@StartBracket@@+8.0@@EndBracket@@. }
