1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. d4 cxd4
4. Nxd4 { Open Variation } 4... d5
{ Nimzo-American Variation, A rather dubious move, challenging White's center pawn. }
5. Nxc6
{ Trading Knights.   A good alternative is  5.exd5  Qxd5  6.Be3  @@StartBracket@@+1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
5... bxc6 6. exd5 { Trading a pair of center pawns. } 6... cxd5
{ Recapturing with the pawn is a big mistake.   6...Qxd5  would have been a better move @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Bb5+ Bd7
{ The only way to block the check without losing a lot of material... But because of this move, the Queen no longer defends the pawn on  d5  . }
8. Qxd5
{ Capturing an important center pawn @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@. } 8...
Qa5+
{ Check, while attacking the Bishop on  b5  with a second piece. The most played move, but this is a game-ending blunder, because it leaves both the Rook and the Bishop unprotected. }
9. Nc3 { Blocking the check while defending  b5  . } 9... Rd8
{ Bringing the Rook into safety while defending the Bishop. But Black must have overlooked White's next move...   9...Bxb5  loses to  10.Qxa8+  Qd8  11.Qxd8+  Kxd8  12.Nxb5  @@StartBracket@@+9.0@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Bxd7+
{ Check, with a discovered attack on the Queen! The Queen can't be saved... }
10... Rxd7 11. Qxa5
{ White is up a lot of material and should easily win the game @@StartBracket@@+12.5@@EndBracket@@. }
