[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Sicilian Defense, Old Sicilian Variation"]
[Black "Old Sicilian Variation, Open, Accelerated Dragon Variation, Modern Bc4 Variation (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. d4 cxd4
4. Nxd4 { Open Variation } 4... g6 { Accelerated Dragon Variation } 5. Nc3
{ Modern Variation } 5... Bg7 { Attacking the Knight in the center. } 6. Be3
{ Defending the Knight. } 6... Nf6
{ Developing the second Knight, getting ready to castle. } 7. Bc4
{ Modern Bc4 Variation, Keeping an eye on  f7  . } 7... O-O 8. Bb3 Na5
{ Attacking the Bishop. It isn't easy to spot how to punish this blunder if you haven't seen these lines before. The problem is that this move takes away an important flight square for the Queen a few moves later in this variation. }
9. e5
{ A very strong pawn push. This is the starting point of some amazing attacking lines! There is no longer a Knight on  c6  to prevent this move from being played. }
9... Ne8
{ The most played reply, yet another blunder.   Black's only chance to stay in the game is  9...Nxb3  , although he is in bad shape after  10.exf6  Nxa1  11.fxg7  @@StartBracket@@+1.5@@EndBracket@@.   9...Nh5  fails to  10.g4!  , trapping the Knight @@StartBracket@@+3.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Bxf7+ { A brilliant Bishop sacrifice. } 10... Kxf7
{ It doesn't matter if and how Black recaptures.   10...Rxf7  will be followed by  11.Ne6  , trapping Black's Queen.  11...dxe6  12.Qxd8  @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@.   10...Kh8  fails to  11.Ne6  again, trapping the Queen @@StartBracket@@+8.0@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Ne6
{ Another brilliant move, attacking the Queen with the Knight. The Queen is trapped! She would love to go to  a5  but that square is already occupied by a Knight. }
11... Kxe6
{ A game-ending blunder.   11...dxe6  actually is Black's best move.  12.Qxd8  will be White's reply. That's how bad his position is @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Qd5+ { The first move of a mate-in-6. } 12... Kf5 13. g4+ Kxg4 14. Rg1+ Kh4
{ 14...Kf5  15.Rg5#  ,   14...Kh3  15.Qg2+  Kh4  16.Qg4#  ,   14...Kh5  15.Qg2  , followed by  Qg4#  or  Qg5#  , depending on Black's reply. }
15. Qe4+ Kh3
{ 15...Kh5  16.Qg4#  ,   15...Kh3  16.Rg3+  Kxh2  17.Qg2#  ,   15...Rf4  16.Qxf4+  Kh5  17.Qg5#  . }
16. Qg4+ Kxh2 17. Qg3# *

