1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Old Sicilian Variation } 3. Bc4
{ Keeping an eye on  f7  . After 2... Nc6, less than 0.2% of all Master games continued with 3. Bc4. But for non-Master games, this is a stunning 14.7%.  The suspicion is that a lot of players are not aware of the fact that this is not an Italian game, because of the pawn on  c5  instead of  e5  . }
3... d6 4. Ng5 { Threatening a Knight fork on  f7  . } 4... e6
{ Blocking the diagonal for the Bishop while threatening to capture the Knight next move. }
5. Qf3
{ Threatening checkmate, but overlooking Black's next move. This is the most frequently played blunder after White chose Bc4 on move 3.   A move like  5.Nc3  is equally bad for the same reason, namely  5...Qxg5  @@StartBracket@@-5.5@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Qxg5
{ Capturing a full piece for free @@StartBracket@@-5.5@@EndBracket@@. Don't just focus on your own attack, but also pay close attention to the moves your opponent plays!  Similar frequently played positions with identical tactics occur, e.g. in case Black played 3... g6 or 3... a6 instead of 3... d6. }
