[Black "Modern Variation, Ginsberg Gambit (2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Bc4 { Ginsberg Gambit, Leaving the pawn on  e4  unprotected. } 5... Nxe4
{ Grabbing White's remaining center pawn. But at what cost? } 6. Qh5
{ Launching an attack on  f7  . } 6... e6 { Blocking the Bishop's diagonal. }
7. Bb5+ { A very interesting check. You'll see why! } 7... Bd7
{ 7...Nd7  would have been more accurate @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Nxe6
{ A very nice move: Grabbing an important pawn while attacking the Queen. The Knight can't be taken because the pawn on  f7  is pinned to the King. }
8... Qa5+ { The most common move in this position. But this is a mistake. } 9.
Bd2 { Attacking the Queen. The Queen has to prevent a Knight fork on  c7  . }
9... Nxd2
{ This game-ending blunder is the most common reply.   9...Qb6  was the move Black needed to find. After  10.Be3  , White is better @@StartBracket@@+1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Bxd7+ { Check, with a discovered attack on Black's Queen! } 10... Nxd7 11.
Qxa5 { White is up a lot of material @@StartBracket@@+7.5@@EndBracket@@. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Sicilian Defense, Modern and French Variations"]
[Black "Modern Variation, Classical Variation, Venice Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 { Attacking White's Knight, a dubious move. } 6. Bb5+
{ Venice Attack, A zwischenzug! } 6... Bd7
{ Blocking the check with the precious light-squared Bishop.   6...Nbd7  is slightly better @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Bxd7+ { White is happy to trade of the light-squared Bishops. } 7... Nbxd7
{ 7...Qxd7  is slightly better @@StartBracket@@+1.0@@EndBracket@@. } 8. Nf5
{ Attacking the pawn on  d6  , while keeping an eye at the pawn on  g7  . The Bishop on  f8  now has to keep defending  g7  .   8...Nc5  is the alternative. But after  9.Bg5  g6  10.Ne3  , White's Knights are heading for the fantastic outpost in the center @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8... g6 { Chasing away the Knight is a blunder. } 9. Nxd6+
{ Grabbing a free pawn with check. } 9... Bxd6
{ Trading a pair of minor pieces. } 10. Qxd6
{ White won a pawn and has a dominant position @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
