[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 { Classical Variation } 6. Bc4
{ Sozin Attack, Keeping an eye on  f7  . } 6... g6
{ With the idea to fianchetto the Bishop next move. } 7. Nxc6
{ Trading a pair of Knights. This opens up the d-file for the Queen AND reloves one defender of Black's Queen. You'll see why that's important! }
7... bxc6 8. e5
{ Magnus Smith Trap, Sacrificing a pawn, attacking the Knight on  f6  . } 8...
dxe5
{ Black took the bait and fell into a trap! This blunder opens up the d-file, allowing a neat tactic for White.   8...Ng4  would have been a better move, keeping the d-file closed @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bxf7+ { A Bishop sacrifice, luring the King away from the Queen. } 9... Kxf7
10. Qxd8
{ White can freely capture the unprotected Queen @@StartBracket@@+7.5@@EndBracket@@. A similar tactic occurs with 6... a6 instead of 6... g6. }
