[White "3. Sicilian Defense, Modern and French Variations"]
[Black "Modern Variation, Classical Variation, Richter-Rauzer Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 { Classical Variation } 6. Bg5
{ Richter-Rauzer Variation, Attacking the Knight on  f6  . } 6... e5
{ Claiming space in the center while attacking the Knight on  d4  . In some variations of the Sicilian, e5 is a good move. But in this variation, it isn't. }
7. Bxf6 { Trading a pair of minor pieces. } 7... Qxf6
{ Black usually prefers an intact pawn structure.   7...gxf6  would have been better, because in that case the Queen keeps defending  c7  @@StartBracket@@+1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Ndb5
{ Threatening a fork on  c7  and making use of the fact that the Queen doesn't protect  c7  anymore. }
8... Qd8
{ Bringing the Queen back, defending  c7  .   8...Rb8  or even  8...Kb8  would have been better. That's how bad Black's position is @@StartBracket@@+2.5@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nd5
{ The second Knight joins the attack. The Knights are threatening a Knight fork on  c7  , forking King and Rook on  a8  . }
9... Qa5+ { A desperate try. } 10. c3
{ White should keep the Knights where they are and block the check with a pawn @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@.   A Queentrade with  10.Qd2  isn't good for White, because she can join the attack later in the game, e.g. by putting pressure on  d6  @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@.  This variation is very similar to a position in theOld Sicilian Variation, Open, Lasker-Pelikán Variation we've seen earlier. }
