[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Sicilian Defense, Modern and French Variations"]
[Black "Modern Variation, Dragon Variation, Levenfish Variation (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Dragon Variation, With the idea to fianchetto the dark-squared Bishop next move. }
6. f4 { Levenfish Variation, Preparing an aggressive pawn push. } 6... Bg7
{ 6...Nc6  is a less risky move, because it prevents White from playing  e5  @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
7. e5
{ Attacking the Knight on  f6  .   Stockfish likes other moves too in this position, e.g.  7.Bb5  . But  7.e5  will probably give you the best results in practice. }
7... dxe5
{ 7...Nh5  is a solid reply.  8.g4  isn't a good idea because of  8...Nxf4  9.Bxf4  dxe5  , forking two of White's minor pieces @@StartBracket@@-2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8. fxe5 { Attacking the Knight on  f6  once again. } 8... Nd5
{ The second most popular move... But not a good one! } 9. Bb5+
{ Checking the King. } 9... Kf8
{ 9...Bd7  fails to  10.Nxd5  @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@.   And  9...Nc6  is bad in view of  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Bxc6  , forking King and Rook @@StartBracket@@+7.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10. O-O
{ A very calm but superior move, lining up the Rook with Black's King. White leaves the pawn on  e5  unprotected on purpose! }
10... Bxe5
{ 10...Nxc3?  loses immediately to  11.Ne6+  Kg8  12.Qxd8+  Bf8  13.Qxf8#  . }
11. Nxd5
{ I personally prefer this move order. Almost all Black players will recapture the Knight, a bad move! }
11... Qxd5 12. Bh6+
{ Activating the dark-squared Bishop with check.   12...Bg7  fails to  13.Bc4  , with an attack on the Queen and the pawn on  f7  behind her @@StartBracket@@+10.5@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Kg8 13. Nf5
{ A killer move: threatening Nxe7# while attacking the Queen on  d5  . } 13...
Qc5+ 14. Be3
{ It is important to keep attacking Black's pieces, since a passive move like  14.Kh1?  allows Black to stay in the game with  14...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Qc7 { Defending against a checkmate on the back rank. } 15. Nh6+
{ The first move of a mate-in-2. } 15... Kg7 { 15...Kf8  16.Rxf7#  . } 16.
Rxf7# { A beautiful sequence ending with a cool checkmate! } *

