[Black "Modern Variation, Najdorf Variation, Lipnitsky Attack (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Najdorf Variation, One of the most popular variations among grandmasters. }
6. Bc4 { Lipnitsky Attack, Keeping an eye on  f7  . } 6... b5
{ Attacking the Bishop. } 7. Bb3 b4
{ This inaccurate move was played over 1,000 times! } 8. Nd5
{ The best reply, threatening to capture the pawn on  b4  . } 8... Nxe4
{ By far the most played move in this position. But this is a blunder!   8...e6  would have been better, in view of  9.Nxf6+  @@StartBracket@@+1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Qf3
{ Attacking the Knight in the center while keeping an eye on the Rook on  a8  . }
9... Nc5
{ 9...Nf6  fails to  10.Nxf6+  gxf6  11.Qxa8  , winning a full Rook @@StartBracket@@+7.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Nxb4 { Grabbing a pawn, while opening up two important diagonals. } 10...
Nxb3 { Trading a pair of minor pieces, attacking the Rook on  a1  . } 11. axb3
{ Opening up the a-file for the Rook on  a1  . White's Queen still attacks the Rook on  a8  . }
11... Ra7 { Saving the Rook. } 12. Ndc6
{ Forking Queen and Rook while opening up the  g1  -  a7  diagonal. We'll see in a moment why that's important. }
12... Nxc6 { Trading Knights. } 13. Nxc6 { Forking Queen and Rook again. }
13... Bb7 { Attacking the Knight while pinning it to the Queen. } 14. Qe3
{ Counter-attacking the Rook. Remember that Black still has to deal with the Knight... }
14... Bxc6 15. Qxa7
{ White is up the exchange while Black needs at least three more moves to castle his King @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

