1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Najdorf Variation, One of the most popular variations among grandmasters. }
6. Bc4 { Lipnitsky Attack, Keeping an eye on  f7  . } 6... b5
{ Attacking the Bishop. } 7. Bb3 Bb7
{ Attacking the pawn on  e4  with two minor pieces. } 8. O-O
{ Deliberately ignoring the threat on  e4  . } 8... Nxe4
{ Black falls into the trap. This blunder is close to game-ending! } 9. Qf3
{ Threatening to capture the pawn on  f7  with check, while attacking the Knight on  e4  and the Bishop behind it. }
9... d5
{ The best move.   9...Nc5  fails to  10.Qxf7+  Kd7  11.Be6+  Nxe6  12.Nxe6  @@StartBracket@@+9.0@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Nxe4 { Trading a pair of Knights. } 10... dxe4
{ Recapturing the Knight but reopening up the diagonal for the Bishop! } 11.
Qxf7+
{ The first move of a mate-in-12. But in practice, Black will probably be getting checkmated after much less moves. }
11... Kd7 12. Ne6 { Attacking the Queen while threatening Rd1+. } 12... Qb6
{ 12...Qc8  loses to  13.Rd1+  Kc6  14.Qf5  Kb6  15.Be3+  Ka5  16.Rd4  Nc6  17.Ra4#  . }
13. Rd1+ Kc6
{ Instead, Black could survive a couple more moves by sacrificing the Bishop and Queen. }
14. Qe8+ Nd7 15. Qxd7# *

