[Black "Modern Variation, Najdorf Variation, English Attack "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Najdorf Variation, One of the most popular variations among grandmasters. }
6. Be3
{ English Attack, With the idea to create a Queen and Bishop battery along the  c1  -  h6  diagonal. }
6... b5
{ With the idea to play b4 next move, chasing away the defender of the pawn on  e4  . }
7. a4 { Challenging the pawn on  b5  . } 7... b4
{ A rather poor move.   7...bxa4  would have been better @@StartBracket@@+1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Nd5
{ White's only move to get an edge, leaving the pawn on  e4  unprotected on purpose! }
8... Nxe4
{ A very poor move. But it is hard to see why this is the case, if you haven't seen this variation before.   8...e6  is best, followed by  9.Nxf6+  Qxf6  10.Qd2  @@StartBracket@@+1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nb5
{ An absolutely brilliant move, threatening a Knight fork on  c7  . Almost impossible to find by yourself, but by far the best move in the position! }
9... axb5 { Capturing the Knight on  b5  , preventing a Knight fork on  c7  . }
10. Bxb5+
{ The most forcing line.   10.Bb6  may be even better, but Black can complicate the position in some variations. }
10... Bd7
{ 10...Nd7  runs into  11.Bb6  , trapping Black's Queen @@StartBracket@@+7.0@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Bb6
{ Attacking the Queen while defending the  c7  square for the Knight to join the attack next move. }
11... Qc8 12. Nc7+ { Check, forking King and Rook. } 12... Kd8
{ 12...Qxc7  is the best move here, that's how bad Black's position really is @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Nxa8+ { Discovered check, while grabbing a Rook. } 13... Ke8 14. Nc7+
{ White is up in material and has a very dominant position @@StartBracket@@+9.0@@EndBracket@@. }
