[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. Nf3 d6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Najdorf Variation, One of the most popular variations among grandmasters. }
6. Be3
{ English Attack, With the idea to create a Queen and Bishop battery along the  c1  -  h6  diagonal. }
6... Ng4 { Anti-English, Trying to trade off the Bishop on  e3  for a Knight. }
7. Bf4 { A blunder, played hundreds of times! } 7... e5
{ Forking two minor pieces. This move is more powerful in the 5... a6 variation instead of the 5... Nc6 variation. In the latter variant, White can trade Knights and prevent a loss of material. }
8. Nf5
{ A sneaky reply: Saving one of the minor pieces while cutting communication between the Bishop on  c8  and the Knight on  g4  .   A move like  8.h3  fails to  8...Nf6  . White can't save both pieces @@StartBracket@@-3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Nxf2 { Not many players were able to find the best move. } 9. Kxf2 exf4
{ Only now you can safely capture the Bishop. Black won a pawn and has the Bishop pair, although he is behind in development @@StartBracket@@-1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
