[White "4. Sicilian Defense, Other Variations"]
[Black "Sicilian Defense, Alapin Variation, Barmen Defense (4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 { Sicilian Defense } 2. c3 { Alapin Variation, Preparing d4. } 2... d5
{ Challenging White's pawn on  e4  . } 3. exd5
{ Trading a pair of center pawns. } 3... Qxd5
{ Barmen Defense, Recapturing the pawn with the Queen. Note that the Queen can't be chased away by a Knight, because there already is a pawn on  c3  . }
4. d4 { Fighting for center control. } 4... cxd4
{ Trading yet another pair of center pawns. } 5. cxd4 Nc6
{ Attacking  d4  with a second piece. } 6. Nf3
{ Defending  d4  with a second piece. } 6... Bg4
{ Attacking one of the defenders of the pawn on  d4  while pinning it to the Queen. }
7. Be2 { Unpinning the Knight while defending it. } 7... Nf6 8. Nc3
{ Kicking back Black's Queen. } 8... Qd8
{ A big blunder according to Stockfish 13. The point is that   8...Qa5  would have been better, e.g. followed by  9.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@+0.5@@EndBracket@@. }
9. d5
{ Attacking the Knight by moving the d-pawn forward. This is the only move that gives White a huge edge. }
9... Nb4
{ Another very poor move, played dozens of times.   9...Bxf3  is best. White should continue with  10.gxf3  in order to keep  Bb5+  possible @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@.   And after  9...Nb8?  , White can extend his lead by playing  10.Bf4  . It will take several move moves for Black to bring his King into safety. White has a huge development advantage @@StartBracket@@+4.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Qa4+
{ Check, forking King and Knight on  b4  . White will win the Knight and the game @@StartBracket@@+7.0@@EndBracket@@. }
