{ Thanks to this in-between move, black has to make difficult choices in the coming moves that may have major consequences. }
6... Nd7
{ This move is Black's favorite option, but it actually is a poor move.   6...Bc6  and  6...c6  are Black's safest options @@StartBracket@@+1.0@@EndBracket@@.   6...Nc6  allows  7.Ne5  . The game could continue with  7...Qd5  8.Qe2  Nf6  9.f3  O-O-O  10.Bxc6  Bxc6  @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Ne5
{ Attacking the Knight on  d7  once more! It cannot move since it is pinned to the King by the Bishop. }
7... Bxe4
{ Black usually captures the Knight in the center.   7...c6  8.Nxc6  would have been a bit better @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Bxd7+
{ It is very important to capture with the Bishop instead of with the Knight!   After  8.Nxd7+?  c6  , White will lose some material @@StartBracket@@-2.5@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Ke7 9. Bc6
{ Attacking both the Rook and the Bishop @@StartBracket@@+7.5@@EndBracket@@. White has a strong attack, and Black will have a hard time to develop his pieces on the kingside. In case the Bishop gets taken, the Knight will recapture and fork King and Queen. }
