[Black "French Defense, Rubinstein Variation, Fort Knox Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 { French Defense } 2. d4 { Normal Variation } 2... d5 3. Nc3
{ Paulsen Variation } 3... dxe4 { Rubinstein Variation } 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6
{ Fort Knox Variation, Attacking the Knight. } 6. Bd3 { Defending the Knight. }
6... Nf6 { Attacking the Knight with a second piece. } 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ A blunder. Instead,  7...gxf6  is the only move that keeps Black in the game. }
8. Bg5 { Trapping the Queen! } 8... Bxf3
{ Removing the defender of both  d4  and  g5  . Did White make a mistake? } 9.
Qd2
{ Protecting the Bishop on  g5  while defending  d4  tactically. Black's Queen is still trapped. }
9... Qxd4
{ A desperate try...   9...Bxg2  would have been better. After  10.Bxf6  Bxh1  11.Bh4  , the material is about equal, but the Queen should give White a big advantage in the rest of the game @@StartBracket@@+4.0@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Bb5+
{ Check, while Black's Queen is under attack! Black will soon lose the Queen and the game @@StartBracket@@+7.0@@EndBracket@@. }
