[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 { French Defense } 2. d4 { Normal Variation } 2... d5 3. Nc3
{ Paulsen Variation } 3... dxe4 { Rubinstein Variation } 4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ This move was played the most.   4...Nd7  would have been a bit better, preparing  Ngf6  . The point is that after White captures on  f6  , Black now can recapture on  f6  with the Knight instead of with the Queen. }
5. Bd3
{ 5.Nxf6+  is slightly better, as we've seen in the previous variation. } 5...
Qxd4
{ Black thinks White blundered a pawn, but reality will soon be revealed.   A similar position arises after  5...Nc6  6.Nf3  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  Qxd4  . }
6. Bb5+ { Check! Note that Black's Queen is under attack. } 6... c6
{ A desperate try... } 7. Qxd4
{ White wins the Queen and the game @@StartBracket@@+7.0@@EndBracket@@.   Don't fall for  7.Bxc6+??  Nxc6!  Black's Queen now is defended again! Suddenly Black is totally winning @@StartBracket@@-7.0@@EndBracket@@. }
