{ Paulsen Variation } 3... Nf6 { Classical Variation } 4. e5
{ Steinitz Variation } 4... Nfd7 5. Nf3 c5 6. dxc5 { A surprising trade. } 6...
Bxc5 7. Bd3 { Develpoing a piece, getting ready to castle. } 7... Nc6
{ Developing a piece while attacking  e5  . } 8. Bf4 { Defending  e5  . } 8...
Qb6 { A nice developing move, eyeing at  b2  and  f2  . } 9. O-O
{ Castling calmly. The best move! } 9... Qxb2
{ Black risks to take a poisoned pawn. But at what cost? } 10. Nb5
{ The only move for White to have a big advantage, threatening Nc7 and some other nasty stuff as we will see in a moment. }
10... O-O { The most played and most natural reply. } 11. Bxh7+
{ Sacrificing a Bishop out of nowhere! } 11... Kxh7 12. Ng5+
{ Moving forward with check. } 12... Kg8 13. Qd3
{ A key move to remember: Threatening checkmate on  h7  while defending  c2  .   13.Qh5  is losing because of  13...Qxc2  , covering  h7  . }
13... Rd8
{ Making sure the King has some squares available to avoid checkmate... } 14.
Qh7+ Kf8 15. Rfb1
{ The point of the whole sequence: Black's Queen is trapped @@StartBracket@@+5.0@@EndBracket@@! }
