[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. French Defense"]
[Black "French Defense, Advance Variation (2)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 { French Defense } 2. d4 { Normal Variation } 2... d5 3. e5
{ Advance Variation } 3... f6
{ Moving your f-pawn in the early game often is a bad idea.  3...c5  would have been better: attacking the basis of White's pawn chain. }
4. Nf3
{ The most played move in this position, although not the best one.   4.Bd3  would have been slightly better, keeping the d1-h5 diagonal open for the Queen, as we will see in the next variation. }
4... fxe5 { This is the main reason why  f6  was played. } 5. Nxe5
{ A perfect outpost for the Knight in the center of the board at move 5! The Knight cannot be easily chased away due to the lack of the f-pawn. }
5... Bd6 { Trying to dislodge the Knight, but overlooking White's reply... } 6.
Qh5+ g6
{ Other moves result in a checkmate:  6...Ke7  or  6...Kf8  both can be followed by  7.Qf7#  . }
7. Nxg6
{ Attacking the Rook. If the Knight is captured, the Queen can capture the Rook. }
7... Nf6 { Chasing away the Queen. } 8. Qh4
{ The Queen has to stay on the h-file in order to make sure Black can't win the Knight for free. Unlike the previous example, the pawn on  e6  is defended, so Qh3 wouldn't make any sense. }
8... Rg8 { Saving the Rook. } 9. Ne5
{ The only move for White to keep an edge @@StartBracket@@+3.5@@EndBracket@@.   Note that  9.Nf4  fails to  9...Rg4  , forking Queen and Knight. White has to make sure the Queen doesn't get trapped @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

