[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. French Defense"]
[Black "French Defense, Advance Variation (3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 { French Defense } 2. d4 { Normal Variation } 2... d5 3. e5
{ Advance Variation } 3... Nc6
{ Not the best move for Black. In the French Defense, Black can often put pressure on the basis of White's pawn structure with the move  c7  -  c5  . Because of this Knight move, the c-pawn temporary can't move. }
4. Nf3 f6 { An attempt to gain more control over the center. } 5. Bb5
{ Pinning Black's only developed piece. } 5... fxe5 { A very poor move. } 6.
Nxe5
{ One move ago, White's own pawns prevented the Knight from occupying the center. But after Black's last move, White is able jump with his Knight to an ideal square in the middle of the board. }
6... Bd7
{ Protecting the Knight once more. The Knight on  c6  was attacked twice, and it couldn't move due to a pin. }
7. Bxc6
{ A deep move. The most played move in this position is  7.Qh5+  . But after  7...g6  8.Nxg6  Nf6  9.Qh4  hxg6  10.Qxh8  , the pawn on  d4  is hanging:  10...Nxd4  11.Bxd7+  Kxd7  . White is slightly better, but Black has a threat on  c2  and is better developed. }
7... Bxc6 8. Qh5+
{ Only now a check is good! The pawn on  d4  will not hang anymore at the end of the sequence since the Knight on  c6  is gone. }
8... g6 9. Nxg6
{ Attacking the Rook. If the Knight is captured, the Queen can capture the Rook. }
9... Nf6 { Chasing away the Queen. } 10. Qh3
{ The Queen has to stay on the h-file in order to make sure Black can't win the Knight for free. Note that both the pawn on  e6  and the Rook on  h8  are under attack. }
10... Rg8 { Saving the Rook. } 11. Qxe6+
{ Capturing yet another pawn. White is up two pawns @@StartBracket@@+4.0@@EndBracket@@. }
