{ Advance Variation } 3... c5 { Attacking the pawn on  d4  . } 4. c3
{ Defending  d4  . } 4... Nc6 { Attacking  d4  . } 5. Nf3
{ Paulsen Attack, Defending  d4  . } 5... cxd4
{ Trading a pair of center pawns. } 6. cxd4
{ This position can also be reached via the Old Sicilian:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.c3  e6  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  d5  6.e5  ,  or via the Alapin Variation of the Sicilian Defense:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.cxd4  e6  5.Nf3  d5  6.e5  . }
6... Bb4+ { Not the most accurate move. } 7. Nc3
{ Blocking the check while developing a Knight. } 7... Nge7
{ Black is getting ready to castle, so it is time to set a nice trap. } 8. Bd3
{ Eyeing  h7  . } 8... O-O { A blunder! Can you spot why? } 9. Bxh7+
{ Sacrificing the Bishop with check!  This is a typical example of the 'Greek Gift', a common tactical theme, where one side sacrifices their Bishop for a pawn by playing Bxh7+  (as White)  or Bxh2+  (as Black)  after the opponent castled kingside, usually in order to checkmate the opponent or gain significant material advantage. }
9... Kxh7
{ 9...Kh8  should be met with  10.Ng5  @@StartBracket@@+8.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Ng5+
{ Check, while opening the diagonal for the Queen to join the attack. } 10...
Kg8 11. Qh5 { Threatening checkmate on  h7  . } 11... Re8
{ Creating an escape square for the King. } 12. Qh7+ Kf8 13. Qh8+ Ng8 14. Nh7+
Ke7 15. Bg5+ { Checking the King while eyeing at the Queen behind the King. }
15... f6
{ The final blunder...   15...Nf6  16.Qxg7  @@StartBracket@@+7.5@@EndBracket@@. }
16. Qxg7# { The end of a very interesting attack! } *

