{ This position can also be reached via the Old Sicilian:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.c3  e6  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  d5  6.e5  ,  or via the Alapin Variation of the Sicilian Defense:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.cxd4  e6  5.Nf3  d5  6.e5  . }
6... Nge7 { Developing the second Knight, ready to jump to  f5  . } 7. Bg5
{ Pinning the Knight on  e7  to the Queen, a poor move. } 7... Qb6
{ Unpinning the Queen while attacking the pawn on  b2  . } 8. b3
{ Saving the pawn this way is a blunder.   8.Qd2  or even  8.Nc3  would have been better @@StartBracket@@+0.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Nf5 { Attacking  d4  with a third piece. } 9. Be3 { Defending  d4  . }
9... Bb4+ { A nasty check to deal with. } 10. Nbd2
{ The best move.   10.Bd2  loses to  10...Nfxd4  @@StartBracket@@-4.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Bc3
{ Attacking the Rook and the pawn on  d4  . The following moves serve to get the Rook to  c2  , you will see in a moment why that is important. }
11. Rc1 Bb2 12. Rc2 Bxd4
{ Grabbing a pawn in the center with the Bishop that was being attacked. } 13.
Nxd4 { Trading a pair of minor pieces. } 13... Ncxd4
{ It is important to recapture the Knight with the c-Knight instead of the f-Knight. The f-Knight has to keep an eye on the Bishop on  e3  . }
14. Bxd4 { Trading another pair of minor pieces. } 14... Nxd4
{ You should recapture with the Knight. Black now keeps the initiative because that Knight attacks the Rook on  c2  @@StartBracket@@-3.0@@EndBracket@@.   14...Qxd4  is less good in view of  15.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@-1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
*

