1. e4 d5 2. Nf3 { Tennison Gambit } 2... dxe4
{ Attacking the Knight on  f3  . } 3. Ng5 { Attacking Black's center pawn. }
3... Nf6 { Defending the pawn on  e4  . } 4. Nc3 { Attacking  e4  once more. }
4... Bf5 { Trying to keep the extra pawn. } 5. Qe2
{ Attacking  e4  once more, hoping that Black will blunder next move. } 5...
Qd4
{ The most played move in this position, but this is a big blunder. Black wanted to hold on to the pawn, but at what cost? }
6. Qb5+
{ What a move! Giving check while attacking  b7  and the Bishop on  f5  . This is the reason why White played a few suboptimal moves: To trick Black in defending the pawn with as many pieces as possible. }
6... Bd7 { The most played reply, saving the Bishop. } 7. Qxb7
{ Grabbing a pawn and attacking the Rook on  a8  . } 7... Bc6
{ Black probably still thinks he has everything under control.   7...Qb6  is a bit better. After  8.Qxa8  Bc6  , it looks like the Queen is trapped. White now has to find  9.Bb5!  @@StartBracket@@+5.5@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Bb5
{ A killer move! The Bishop can't capture the Queen anymore since it is pinned to the King. White is totally winning @@StartBracket@@+8.5@@EndBracket@@.   Moves like  8...Qb6  or  8...Qc5  will end up with  9.Qc8#  . }
8... Qd7
{ Protecting the Bishop while preventing checkmate on  c8  .   8...Bxb5  9.Nxb5  is an alternative. }
9. Bxc6 { A very strong move, renewing the threat of Qxa1. } 9... Qxc6
{ Protecting the Rook, but overlooking White's reply... } 10. Qc8#
{ Checkmate. What a nice attack! } *

