[White "6. Scandinavian Defense"]
[Black "Scandinavian Defense, Mieses-Kotrč Variation (6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 { Scandinavian Defense } 2. exd5 Qxd5 { Mieses-Kotrč Variation } 3.
Nc3 { Attacking the Queen while developing the Knight. } 3... Qd8
{ Retreating the Queen all the way back to its starting square. } 4. d4
{ Expanding in the center. } 4... Nc6
{ Developing a piece while attacking  d4  once more. An inaccurate move. } 5.
Nf3
{ Defending  d4  .   Objectively,  5.d5  Nb8  is a bit stronger @@StartBracket@@+2.0@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bg4
{ Attacking the defender of  d4  , pinning the Knight to the Queen. The most played move in this position, but a bad one! }
6. d5
{ Advancing the center pawn, attacking the Knight. By far the strongest move in the position. }
6... Ne5
{ A seemingly natural move, putting pressure on White's pinned  f3  Knight. }
7. Nxe5 { A brilliant Queen sacrifice! } 7... Bxd1
{ If Black doesn't accept the sacrifice, he will be a piece down. } 8. Bb5+
{ Black's King now is in serious danger. } 8... c6 9. dxc6
{ Threatening  c7  with a discovered check. } 9... a6
{ Attacking White's most dangerous piece. } 10. c7+
{ Ready to promote the pawn while checking the King with the Bishop. } 10...
axb5 { 10...Qd7?  11.Bxd7#  is checkmate. } 11. cxd8=Q+
{ Promoting to a Queen with check. } 11... Rxd8 12. Nxd1
{ White won a full piece in the attack. Black's kingside isn't developed at all, and his queenside pawns are shattered @@StartBracket@@+5.5@@EndBracket@@. The whole sequence is very similar as the sequence in theNimzowitsch Defense, Williams Variation }
