[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 { Scandinavian Defense } 2. exd5 Qxd5 { Mieses-Kotrč Variation } 3.
Nc3 { Attacking the Queen while developing the Knight. } 3... Qa5
{ Main Line, Pinning the Knight to the King in case White moves the  d2  pawn. }
4. d4 Nf6 { Mieses Variation } 5. Bd2
{ Developing the Bishop on the same diagonal as Black's Queen, unpinning the Knight. }
5... Nc6
{ Attacking the pawn on  d4  . A careless move. Black doesn't see the upcoming danger. }
6. Bb5
{ Pinning the Knight to the King. The only move for White to get an advantage. }
6... Bd7
{ The usual reply.   This was the last chance for Black to bring his Queen to safety, with  6...Qb4  . After  7.d5  a6  8.Ba4  b5  9.Nxb5!  Qe4+  10.Qe2  axb5  11.Qxe4  Nxe4  12.Bxb5  , White is better @@StartBracket@@+2.5@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Nd5
{ A great multi-purpose move: A discovered attack on the Queen, covering the  b6   square with the Knight, and tactically defending the Bishop with  7...Qxb5  8.Nxc7+  , winning the Queen next move. }
7... Nb4 { Prolonging the suffering... } 8. Bxb4
{ Renewing all previous threats. } 8... Qxb5 9. Nxc7+ { Family fork! } 9... Kd8
10. Nxb5 { Time to resign for Black @@StartBracket@@+9.0@@EndBracket@@. } *

