[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 { Scandinavian Defense } 2. exd5 Qxd5 { Mieses-Kotrč Variation } 3.
Nc3 { Attacking the Queen while developing the Knight. } 3... Qa5
{ Main Line, Pinning the Knight to the King in case White moves the  d2  pawn. }
4. d4 Nf6 { Mieses Variation } 5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Pinning the Knight to the Queen while developing the light-squared Bishop. The most played move in this position, but not the best one if White knows how to handle the situation. }
6. h3 { Lasker Variation, The only good move for White. } 6... Bh5
{ Retreating the Bishop while holding on to the pin. } 7. g4
{ Kicking back the Bishop once more. } 7... Bg6 8. Ne5
{ Centralizing the Knight, heading for  c4  . } 8... c6
{ Giving the Queen a few more escape squares. } 9. h4
{ Shifting the game to the other side of the board. } 9... Nbd7
{ Challenging White's Knight in the center. } 10. Nc4 { Attacking the Queen. }
10... Qc7
{ Reatreating the Queen to  c7  , this is the reason why Black played  c6  earlier. }
11. h5 { Attacking Black's Bishop. } 11... Be4
{ The only safe square for the Bishop, attacking the Rook in the corner, defended by the Knight on  f6  . }
12. Nxe4 { Trading pieces. } 12... Nxe4 13. Qf3
{ Activating the Queen, attacking the Knight. } 13... Nd6
{ Retreating the Knight while attacking White's Knight on  c4  .   13...Nef6  14.Bf4  Qc8  puts Black in a very passive position @@StartBracket@@+4.0@@EndBracket@@. }
14. Bf4
{ Pinning the Knight to the Queen. Material is even, but White has a very dominant position @@StartBracket@@+2.5@@EndBracket@@. }
