[Black "Scandinavian Defense, Modern Variation, Portuguese Variation (1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 { Scandinavian Defense } 2. exd5 Nf6 { Modern Variation } 3. d4 Bg4
{ Portuguese Variation } 4. f3
{ The second most played move, attacking the Bishop. } 4... Bf5
{ Retreating the Bishop. The pawn on  f3  is a bit oddly placed. } 5. c4
{ Defending the pawn on  d5  . } 5... e6
{ Inviting White to capture on  e6  , so that the Knight can to jump to  c6  . }
6. dxe6 { Not the best move. The pawn no longer covers the  c6  square. } 6...
Nc6
{ Sacrificing a pawn in exchange for quick development. White's pawn on  d4  is under attack. }
7. exf7+ { Trading a pair of pawns. } 7... Kxf7
{ But this move in fact helps Black to develop even faster. } 8. Be3
{ Defending the pawn on  d4  . } 8... Bb4+
{ Check! The only move to keep an advantage. } 9. Nc3
{ The alternative is  9.Kf2  Re8  , sometimes followed by  10.Nc3  , transposing into the main variation. }
9... Re8
{ Developing the Rook on the open e-file, pinning the Bishop to the King. } 10.
Kf2
{ Unpinning the King while defending the Bishop.   10.Qd2  runs into  10...Nxd4  11.O-O-O  c5  @@StartBracket@@-3.5@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Rxe3
{ This sacrifice is the start of one of the most crazy sequences in this course. }
11. Kxe3 Bc2
{ A brilliant move!   12.Qxc2  fails to  12...Qxd4+  13.Ke2  Re8+  14.Ne4  Nxe4  15.fxe4  Rxe4+  16.Qxe4  Qxe4+  17.Kf2  , with a mate-in-9. After  17.Kd1  instead, Black has a mate-in-2, starting with  17...Nd4  18.Rc1  Qe1#  . }
12. Qd2 { Still defending  d4  . } 12... Ng4+
{ Another brilliant move, opening up the  d8  -  h4  diagonal for the Queen. }
13. fxg4
{ 13.Kf4  will end in a checkmate, after  13...Bd6+  14.Kxg4  Bf5+  15.Kxf5  Qh4!!  Taking away possible escape squares from the white King. White can't stop a checkmate with  g6  . }
13... Qg5+ 14. Ke2 { Still defending the Queen. } 14... Re8+ { Game over! } *

