[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 { Scandinavian Defense } 2. exd5 Nf6 { Modern Variation } 3. Nc3
{ Developing a piece, ready to recapture on  d5  with the Knight. Not the most challenging move. }
3... Nxd5 { Trading pieces. } 4. Nxd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3
{ Both players develop their Knights. } 5... Nc6 6. g3
{ A horrible blunder, although Black will need to find the right moves to punish White. }
6... Bg4
{ Attacking the Knight with a second piece and pinning it to the Queen. } 7.
Bg2 { Defending the Knight with the Bishop. } 7... Ne5
{ Attacking the Knight on  f3  once more.   7...Ne5  is better than  7...Nd4  in view of  8.Nxd4  Qxg2  9.Qxg4  Qxh1+  , and White is 'only' the exchange down. }
8. Nh4
{ White's most challenging reply: Attacking the Queen with the Bishop while defending that Bishop with the Knight. }
8... Qe6
{ A killer move! Black has all kinds of threats, going from a possible queen capture to a discovered check.   8...Nd3+  is possible too, with the idea of  9.cxd3  Qe5+  10.Be4  , winning the Queen. Or  9.Kf1  Qc5  , threatening checkmate on  f2  . }
9. f3
{ The best move would be  9.O-O  , but that move loses the Queen:  9...Bxd1  @@StartBracket@@-7.5@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nxf3+
{ By far the best move in the position: Double check! The only way to escape a double check is by moving your King. }
10. Kf2 { 10.Kf1  runs into  10...Nxh2+  , winning White's Queen next move. }
10... Nxh4
{ Capturing the Knight on  h4  . Black still has multiple threats, it is impossible for White to survive the attack @@StartBracket@@-9.0@@EndBracket@@.   A possible continuation:  11.Qe1  Qf6+  12.Kg1  Nxg2  13.Kxg2  Qf3+  14.Kg1  Bh3  15.Qf2  Qd1+  16.Qf1  Qxf1#  . }
