1. e4 d5 { Scandinavian Defense } 2. exd5 Qxd5 { Mieses-Kotrč Variation } 3.
Nc3 { Attacking the Queen while developing the Knight. } 3... Qa5
{ Main Line, Pinning the Knight to the King in case White moves the  d2  pawn. }
4. d4 Nf6 { Mieses Variation } 5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Pinning the Knight to the Queen while developing the light-squared Bishop. The most played move in this position, but not the best one if White knows how to handle the situation. }
6. Be2
{ Defending the Knight on  f3  .   6.h3  would have been a better move. } 6...
Nc6 { Developing a piece, getting ready to castle queenside. } 7. O-O
{ Again,  7.h3  was a safer option. } 7... O-O-O
{ Castling queenside. White's pawn on  d4  is under pressure. } 8. Be3
{ Defending the  d4  pawn. } 8... e5
{ Increasing the pressure on  d4  .   9.dxe5  fails to  9...Rxd1  . } 9. Nxe5
{ Capturing Black's center pawn is a blunder.   Instead, White should give up the pawn, e.g. with  9.d5  Nxd5  10.Nxd5  @@StartBracket@@-1.5@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nxe5
{ Capturing a free piece.   10.dxe5  is not good because of  10...Rxd1  , losing the Queen for a Rook. }
10. Bxg4+ { Trading pieces, but this doesn't matter too much. } 10... Nexg4
{ Dust has settled. Black is up a piece for a pawn @@StartBracket@@-5.0@@EndBracket@@. }
