[Round "?"]
[White "7. Caro-Kann Defense"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Defense, Two Knights Attack (4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 { Caro-Kann Defense } 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 { Two Knights Attack } 3...
dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { A questionable move, played over 5,000 times. } 5. Ng3
{ Attacking the Bishop on  f5  . } 5... Bg6 6. h4
{ Aiming to trap the Bishop. This position can also occur after:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.Nf3  d5  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  Bg4  5.h3  Bh5  6.Ng3  Bg6  7.h4  . }
6... h6 { Providing a flight square on  h7  for the Bishop. } 7. Ne5
{ Attacking the Bishop again, this time with the other Knight. } 7... Bh7
{ This natural looking move is actually a blunder, played thousands of times. The light-squared Bishop on  h7  is doing almost nothing, and Black's pawns on the light squares  b7  and  f7  are weak, as we will prove in the next sequence of moves.   Black's best continuation is  7...Qd6  , defending the Bishop with the Queen. After  8.d4  Nd7  9.Nxg6  Qxg6  and  10.c3  or  10.Bd3  , White is slightly better @@StartBracket@@+1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Qh5
{ Threatening checkmate on  f7  .   We want to provoke  8...g6  so that the Bishop on  h7  is sidelined. }
8... g6
{ The Bishop on  h7  will not participate in the game for at least ten more moves. }
9. Qf3 { Renewing the checkmate threat on  f7  .   9.Bc4  is also possible. }
9... Nf6 { Defending against checkmate while developing a piece. } 10. Qb3
{ Forking two weak pawns on light squares. } 10... Qd5
{ The only move for Black to resist, blocking the checkmate while attacking the Knight in the center.   10...e6  fails to  11.Qxb7  Nbd7  12.Nxc6  Qc8  13.Ba6  @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Qxb7 { Keeping the initiative. } 11... Qxe5+ 12. Be2 e6
{ The only move where White needs to be very careful not to trap his Queen, as IM Christof Sielecki pointed out in his famous 'Keep It Simple: 1.e4' course. }
13. a4
{ Not intuitive at all, but it is very strong.   13.Qxa8  is not good because of  13...Qc7  , trapping White's Queen.   13.a4  prepares for this scenario by intending to play the pawn up to Black's pawn, to protect the Queen when it returns to  b7  after capturing the Rook. }
13... Bc5
{ This also leads to a lost position, but it is at least somewhat messy. } 14.
c3 { Preparing  d4  next move. } 14... O-O 15. d4 { Forking Queen and Bishop. }
15... Bxd4 16. cxd4 Qa5+ { The best move for Black. } 17. Bd2
{ Blocking the check while attacking the Queen on  a5  . } 17... Qb6
{ Proposing a trade of Queens.   18.Qxa8  would be bad in view of  18...Nd7  , trapping the Queen. }
18. Qxb6 { Trading Queens. Black managed to save his Rook in the corner. }
18... axb6 19. Bxh6
{ Grabbing a free pawn, attacking the Rook @@StartBracket@@+3.5@@EndBracket@@. }
