7... Bh7
{ This poor move was played in 95% of the games... Not illogical, because why else did Black play  h6  previous move?   7...Qd6  is Black's best move. After  8.Bc4  Nd7  , White needs to play accurate to keep an advantage:  9.Qe2  Nxe5  10.dxe5  Qc7  11.e6!  @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Qh5
{ Threatening checkmate on  f7  .   We want to provoke  8...g6  so that the Bishop on  h7  is sidelined. }
8... g6 { The Bishop on  h7  will not participate in the game anytime soon. }
9. Qf3
{ Renewing the checkmate threat on  f7  . Notice that 9. Bc4? is bad in view of 9... Qa5+! Black has created an escape square for the King on  d8  . }
9... Nf6 { Defending against checkmate while developing a piece. } 10. Qb3
{ Forking two weak pawns on light squares. } 10... e6
{ 10...Qd5  fails to  11.Qxb7  , losing the Rook on  a1  @@StartBracket@@+8.5@@EndBracket@@.   10...Nd5  is interesting. But White still should be winning after  11.Qxb7  Nb6  12.Bc4  , threatening checkmate on  f7  while covering  d5  @@StartBracket@@+4.5@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Qxb7 { Attacking the Rook while threatening checkmate again on  f7  . }
11... Nbd7 { Defending against both threats. } 12. Nxc6
{ Winning yet another pawn. } 12... Qc8
{ The only move to save the Queen while keeping an eye on the Rook on  a8  . }
13. Ba6
{ By far the best move. Black will now lose even more material @@StartBracket@@+6.0@@EndBracket@@. }
