{ Trading pawns. } 6. Qxd4 { More than 1,000 players fell into this trap! }
6... Nb6
{ The point of this sequence: There is a double attack on White's Knight while it is pinned to the Queen. }
7. Bb5+ { A zwischenzug, trying to complicate the position. } 7... Nc6
{ Keeping all threats alive while blocking the check. } 8. c4
{ Defending the Knight with a pawn. } 8... e6 { Attacking the pinned Knight. }
9. Bg5
{ Another in-between move. White is hoping for  9...Qxg5??  10.Nc7+  Ke7  11.Qd6#  . }
9... Qd7
{ Stepping aside with the Queen, turning the absolute pin  (to the King)  into a relative pin  (to the Queen)  . }
10. O-O-O { Desperately putting more pressure on the d-file. } 10... exd5
{ Finally capturing White's Knight. } 11. cxd5
{ Attacking the pinned Knight on  c6  . } 11... Nxd4
{ The game could continue with  12.Bxd7+  Bxd7  13.Rxd4  . Black is ahead in material and has the Bishop pair @@StartBracket@@-6.5@@EndBracket@@. }
