{ Attacking the pinned Knight on  f3  twice. } 5. Nxe5
{ Capturing the Knight in the center, sacrificing the Queen!! } 5... Bxd1 6.
Bb5+ { A forcing check. } 6... c6 { The obvious reply. } 7. dxc6
{ Threatening  c7  with a discovered check. } 7... a6
{ Black's best reply.   7...Qa5+  does complicate things a lot. White should respond with  8.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@+2.5@@EndBracket@@. A possible continuation is  8...O-O-O  9.Nc4  Qb4  10.a3  Qc5  11.Be3  Qh5  @@StartBracket@@+3.0@@EndBracket@@. Make sure to check this extremely complicated position with an engine before playing it in a real game! }
8. c7+ { Discovered check while attacking Black's Queen. } 8... axb5 9. cxd8=Q+
{ Promoting to a new Queen. } 9... Rxd8 10. Nxf7
{ Sacrificing the Knight while forking both Rooks is a better continuation than  10.Kxd1  dxe5  @@StartBracket@@+1.0@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Kxf7 11. Kxd1
{ Dust has settled. White is a pawn up and Black's pawn structure is ruined @@StartBracket@@+1.5@@EndBracket@@. The whole sequence is very similar as the sequence in theScandinavian Defense, Mieses-Kotrč Variation }
